    <h1>Minor Harmony Player</h1>
    <p>
    A minor triad is a three-note chord consisting of a root note, a minor third interval above the root, and a perfect fifth interval above the root.
    </p>
    <p>
    In simpler terms, if you start with a note, lets say C, you would add the note three semitones above it (E♭ in the case of a minor third) and then add the note seven semitones above the original note (G). Put them together, and you have a C minor triad (C-E♭-G). The combination of these intervals gives the triad a "minor" sound, which is often described as more somber or melancholic compared to a major triad.
    In summary, a minor triad consists of a root note, a minor third, and a perfect fifth, and it has a distinct, somewhat subdued quality in comparison to a major triad.
    </p>
    <div data-controller ="minortriads">

    <!-- Dropdown for selecting harmonies -->
    <label for="harmonySelect">Select Harmony:</label>
    <select id="harmonySelect">
        <option value="0">C Minor</option>
        <option value="1">F Minor</option>
        <option value="2">G Minor</option>
        <option value="3">A Minor</option>
      <option value="4">D Minor</option>
